description:
In this episode, the tide turns as we explore Whitby Synod. In Yorkshire, England, Celtic Christianity was the dominant faith. This was due to the missionary work of St Aidan, who had been sent over from Iona, Scotland. However, 664 A.D. was a pivotal point where crucial decisions were made, such as the date for Easter. Colman was overruled and left England to return to the Isle of Iona, this then followed with four dark centuries for England. Later, the Danish Vikings swept through England further affecting the future of Christianity in the British Isles, turning the tide away from Celtic Christianity as Paganism returned.

For more information visit our extended article.
